##What happened: Wuhan Hospital staff infected

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

During the surge, infections among health care workers began to appear.

Wuhan's Central Hospital, one of 27 Grade III, Class A hospital, has more than 4,300 staff, according to its website. The former Hankow Catholic hospital has a history of 140 years. There are two hospital districts, Houhu and Nanjing Road, both located in Hankou, which are 5-6 kilometers apart. The latter is less than 2 kilometers away from the South China Seafood Market, this is an important reason why Wuhan Central Hospital was exposed to new cases of pneumonia earlier.

As of February 4, Wuhan Central Hospital in the city designated hospitals, the admission of fever patients second only to Kam Yin Tam Hospital, 510 beds open, 525 beds have been used. However, as of more than a week ago, more than 230 of the staff of Wuhan Central Hospital had reached the clinical criteria for the diagnosis of NCP, of which 130 were hospitalized and more than 100 were isolated at home, a number of department directors and hospital leaders are "in the game. ".

The state of the hospital is a microcosm of Wuhan's health care system.

On February 14, the state new office held a press conference on the latest progress of epidemic prevention and control, especially the initiative to care for medical personnel. As of 2400 hours on February 11, a total of 1,716 cases of new coronavirus pneumonia had been confirmed by medical staff across the country, including 1,502 in Hubei Province and 1,102 in Wuhan, according to the National Health Commission, more than 70% of Hubei.

Test report marked with Red Circle

After graduating from the Tongji Medical College in 1997, she joined Wuhan Central Hospital where she is currently the director of its emergency department. On December 18,2019, a 65-year-old male self-employed person came to the hospital's Nanjing Road Hospital area to see the emergency department, she said. Five days ago, he developed fever with a temperature of 39.1 Â°C and chills before fever, but no symptoms of nasal congestion, runny nose, dyspnea or cough. Previously, on December 16, the man first to the hospital outpatient treatment, after Amoxicillin clavulanate potassium, Oseltamivir and loxson tablets, such as three days of symptomatic treatment no improvement was admitted to the emergency ward. The emergency physician gave the man a high-grade, broad-spectrum carbapenem antibiotic, which showed no improvement, and his lung infection appeared as a "patchy, diffuse shadow on both lungs. ".

The man was transferred to the hospital for medical treatment on 22 December, to Tongji Hospital on 25 December and then to Jinyintan Hospital for infectious patients. In the course of subsequent retracing, Effen learned that the man was a deliveryman at the south China Seafood Market.

On Dec. 27, Avon received a second case of the disease, a 40-year-old man from a remote suburb of Wuhan who had no history of exposure to the south China seafood market. He was treated at a local clinic for more than a week with a high fever, a serious lung infection and 90% oxygen in his fingers. The young man was then admitted to the aspiration department and tested for fiberoptic bronchoscopy and bronchoalveolar lavage fluid. On December 30th tests showed that the man had been infected with a coronavirus. When she saw the words "SARS coronavirus" on the test sheet, she felt "terrible" and immediately reported to the Public Health Department and the hospital department. But whether the hospital reported to the Higher Department of Disease Control was not clear to her.

The test report was posted by Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist at the hospital, on the students'Wechat Group on the afternoon of December 30 and was widely reposted. When a college classmate asked her about the coronavirus in private, Ms. Iffen said, she sent the test back, noting "SARS coronavirus" with a red circle, but did not know how the report got out.

Around the same time, on December 28, the Emergency Department of the hospital's Houhu district received 4 cases of fever related to the south China Seafood Market. As of January 1,2020, the hospital admitted a total of seven "unexplained pneumonia" cases. On December 29, his emergency department reported four of the seven fever cases to the hospital's public health department. Public Health responded that it had been reported to the CDC in Kong Hon. The Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital in Hubei Province and the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital had previously received similar cases, the Kong HON CDC said. Of the four cases reported in the emergency department, a mother and son, a son who worked in the south China Seafood Market, and a mother who went to the seafood market to deliver food, had no contact with the goods of the south China seafood market, but still fell ill and was in a serious condition, efen concluded at the time, the disease can be passed from person to person.

In the early hours of January 1, the Emergency Department of Houhu district received another 65-year-old man who had been transferred from Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. The man, who runs a clinic near the south China Seafood Market, recently admitted a number of patients with fever and later developed symptoms of his own. EFFIN's analysis suggests that the clinic owner's illness was probably transmitted to him by patients at his clinic.

On 1 January, she again reported to the public health and medical services of the hospital that the owner of the clinic had admitted a number of patients in the hope of attracting attention. "If a emergency physician or a nurse gets sick, it's a problem, " she worries.

On December 31, the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission reported 27 cases of "viral pneumonia of unknown origin, " saying that so far no significant human-to-human transmission had been found, and no medical staff infection had been found. In the early hours of this day, Li Wenliang was warned and criticized by the Municipal Health Commission and the hospital. On January 1, Wuhan's Public Security Bureau issued a notice saying eight people had been summoned for "publishing and forwarding false information" .

Shortly before 12 p.m. on January 1, Avon also received a message from the hospital's compliance department asking him to come in the next day for a chat. On January 2, during a talk with the Discipline Inspection Commission, she was criticized by her superiors for "being a professional who has no principles and spreads rumors, and your irresponsible behavior has caused social panic and affected the development and stability of Wuhan, " she said, referring to the disease, which can be transmitted from person to person, but there was no response.

Since January 2, the hospital has asked medical staff not to speak publicly about their condition, not to discuss it through words, pictures or other means that may preserve evidence, and only to mention it orally when it is necessary for the transition. Doctors can not say much about the patients who come to see them.

After hearing the news in early January, Lin Yuan, a nurse at Wuhan's Central Hospital, could only subtly remind her relatives and friends to wear masks.

After reporting the situation to the hospital, but no result, from January 1, effin had to ask his department's medical staff to wear the N95 mask first.

"Comrade" is down

Since January 1, Wuhan's Central Hospital has received an increasing number of cases of fever, like a "volcanic eruption" . In the first week of January, EFFEN's emergency department transformed the Lake District Emergency Surgery Ward into a respiratory isolation ward with about 20 beds. The second week, and the transformation of the emergency medical ward, followed by the Nanjing Road Hospital area will also be transformed into an isolation ward emergency ward. As more and more patients were admitted, all the isolation wards were gradually moved elsewhere, and the emergency medicine and surgery wards were converted into outpatient clinics, which could accommodate more than 50 patients, but still could not accommodate the surge in patients.

Ni Fang is head nurse in respiratory and critical care medicine department. On January 10, the ward in her department was also requisitioned, opening 22 beds. All the beds were filled that day, and the ward she was in charge of was always full.

From mid-to-late January, Wuhan Central Hospital entered the peak period for new crown patients, a state of scarcity continued until the beginning of February. A total of 1,524 patients were admitted to emergency and fever clinics on January 21, including 655 patients with fever, Avon said. About 90 percent of the 1,524 patients were new coronary pneumonia, according to current clinical criteria in Hubei Province. Before the outbreak, the average daily emergency volume in the central hospital was about 550 cases.

During the surge in patients, cases of infection among health care workers began to appear. On January 10, the emergency department found the first case of infection among health care workers, a nurse in the back Lake district. "We later analyzed that she may have been wearing the mask incorrectly, " Ms. Iffen said.

On January 1, emergency medical workers began wearing face masks. On January 10th, he was put into protective clothing. In a few days, the level of protection goes up and you put on a suit. But the number of infected paramedics is increasing. The Emergency Department of the hospital has a total of 200 medical staff, including 50 doctors and 150 nurses. So far, more than 30 people have been diagnosed with lung infections, seven have tested positive for nucleic acid, and effen's team has been "fighting, falling, and replenishing" .

Wuhan General Hospital, paramedics on the front lines. Photo / CCTV news screenshot

The main cause of infection among emergency room staff is their heavy work load, limited space in the emergency room, and the lack of regulation of temporary places to put on and take off their protective clothing, effen said. "All of a sudden, there were so many patients and their families around us, and the density of the virus in the air was too high, " he said. "when the nurses gave the patients injections and drew blood, because of close contact, it caused the infection. " Fortunately, the Emergency Department of Serious Illness, hospital staff is not many.

Ms. Ni said her department had been alert to the disease since early January. "Our department requires that we wear masks, wash our hands frequently and use our hands, " she said. After entering the isolation ward, she put on protective clothing and clothing. About 160 people in the hospital were infected by respiratory and critical care medical staff and about 16 people were infected.

But not all departments have such awareness and equipment. Li Wenliang was one of the early victims at Wuhan Central Hospital. He was infected after seeing an 82-year-old woman with Glaucoma on Jan. 8, "without special protection and without a fever when the patient came in. "

According to China News Week, the medical staff of Wuhan Central Hospital for nosocomial infection are in various departments including thyroid and breast surgery, urology, cardiothoracic surgery, vascular surgery, neurology, digestive medicine and ophthalmology, many of them are department heads. Not long after eye doctor Li Wenliang fell ill, a deputy director of the department was also infected and is being treated by intubation in the hospital.

The head of breast and nail surgery showed symptoms on a CT scan of the lung around January 16, two days after he had been operating on the patient. A deputy chief of CARDIOTHORACIC surgery developed chills on Jan. 22 before an aortic operation was completed, and a high fever was detected after the operation. Colleagues in his department speculated that, the doctor was in close contact with the patient and his family before and after the operation. Among the more serious cases was a chief urologist, three of whom were treated at Wuhan Lung Hospital and the most serious was treated with ECMO. In addition, this time is also infected with the hospital's three deputy director, one of the deputy director of the serious condition.

According to statistics, as of more than a week ago, the Wuhan Central Hospital has reached the clinical diagnostic criteria of new pneumonia staff of more than 230 people, including 130 hospitalized, more than 100 people isolated at home.

"At first, only some departments may know more about the disease, such as the emergency department and the smoking department, but other departments may not, " Dr. Moreover, by Jan. 15, the widespread notion that the new coronavirus was "not apparently transmissible from person to person" had put people and other health care workers at ease.

Wang Yu, a pediatrician at Wuhan General, sees a lot of infectious disease patients. He told China News weekly that he had heard about the admission of such patients in the hospital in early January, but had no idea how contagious and virulent the new coronavirus was, many doctors, including him, initially wore a simple mask to protect themselves. For many surgical departments that do not deal with respiratory infections, it is possible to see a doctor without a mask.

Li Yuan, a nurse at the Central Hospital, is in a front-line department like the non-fever clinic. On Jan. 16, a patient in her department had a suspected infection on a CT scan, and she and her colleagues were alerted to the danger.

Several interviewees said that around January 15, with the side of a "comrade" collapsed, the hospital staff to pay attention to the disease, began to strengthen the protection. CARDIOTHORACIC bought their own N95 masks around here. Around this time, Wang Yu heard that multiple paramedics had been infected in the Wuhan Union Hospital. On January 17, the hospital held an awareness meeting and distributed some relevant information about the disease. Also around this day, Wuhan Tongji Hospital Fever Clinic wearing isolation clothing, protective clothing short video on the Internet.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Without face screens and goggles, the medical staff in the back Lake area of Wuhan's Central Hospital had to use plastic bags instead. (photo provided by interviewee)

We're short on personnel and supplies

17 years ago, Wuhan was not a hard-hit area. Cai Yi, the head of the Pain Department at Wuhan General Hospital, was initially surprised by the "heavily armed" video. "Even though he was aware of it, he didn't know to wear a protective suit, " he said, "Tongji receives a lot of fever patients who may have been aware of the problem earlier. "

When she was in cardiology for SARS, she said, she only emphasized ventilation and masks, and did not wear N95. No one seemed to fall down around her.

After the orientation, Wang Yu started wearing a safety vest to work. However, not all departments can have isolation clothing and protective clothing. "departments that might come into contact with people like colds, fevers and coughs should be equipped, " Wang Yu said. Effin felt that there is no way, after all, this kind of protective materials is not so much, it is difficult to do each one, only priority to ensure key departments. A suspected new crown patient was admitted to the intensive care unit of Ms. Li's department. Colleagues asked if they could issue protective clothing, and the hospital feared that doctors wearing such clothing would cause panic among patients and said it was not yet classified as protective.

On January 21, nurse Zhao Gang went to the isolation ward for support, where he met Li Wenliang and other hospital staff who were being treated in the hospital. At that time, he was admitted to the Ward Hospital staff has more than 20. On January 22, Hankou Hospital became a designated hospital for fever patients and patients admitted to the Central Hospital were temporarily transferred to Hankou Hospital. At Hankou Hospital, Zhao saw nearly 40 staff members suspected of infection at the Central Hospital. And in the last 10 days or so, as health care workers have taken precautions and the number of visits has begun to decline, Dr. iffin said, the number of new cases among hospital staff has also decreased significantly.

From January 21 to the end of January, the Wuhan municipal government has requisitioned three batches of 23 hospitals as designated hospitals for patients with fever, to alleviate the pressure on Wuhan's only two dedicated infectious disease hospitals, Florida Wuhan Lung Hospital and Golden Pool Hospital. The Back Lake Hospital District of Wuhan's Central Hospital, one of the second of three hospitals to be requisitioned, has undergone ward renovation and has been concentrating patients since around January 27. The vast majority of the hospital's specialist out-patient services have also been suspended, set the main force of the hospital, came to support.

On January 29, Fujian and Gansu medical teams from Hubei Province moved into the Wuhan Central Hospital and took over one and two wards in the Houhu Hospital district, respectively. But on February 2, the Fujian medical team was transferred to Wuhan's Jinyintan Hospital, and the Gansu medical team became the only foreign aid to the Central Hospital. The provincial medical team has more than 100 personnel and is responsible for more than 80 patients in two wards. The vast majority of patients in the Central Hospital are treated by their own manpower.

A large number of human input has also brought huge material consumption. Zhao Gang remembers that on the morning of January 21, when he went to the isolation ward of Nanjing Road Hospital to provide support, there were also medical-grade 3m masks that could be worn. At night, the amount of masks was not so sufficient, the head nurse said that the supplies in the back would arrive at any moment. On January 22, the level and quality of protective clothing and masks became a little worse, and after that there were subtle changes in daily supplies.

Ni Fang said that before the Chinese New Year, there might be some reserves of materials, and hospitals might have some channels for procurement, but then with the closure of the city of Wuhan, workers were resting during the Chinese New Year, and supplies were difficult to supply, some do not meet the medical standards, poor quality of protective materials can only be first received, preferential use. Around the New Year, masks, protective clothing in key departments can also be guaranteed, and then more open wards, become in short supply. Without a medical-grade mask, Ni could only wear a surgical mask over an industrial one, a practice that lasted for half a month.

On January 23, Wuhan Central Hospital issued a public appeal for donations. On February 10, three days after Li Wenliang's death, the center hospital again appealed to the public for help. Affected by the Li Wenliang incident, some netizens also voiced that they would no longer donate materials to the center hospital. The reporter learned that the main source of materials for the Central Hospital is social donations, through the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters to transfer a small number. Reporter Calls Wuhan Red Cross and headquarters propaganda department. The Red Cross said it was only responsible for the collection of supplies and assigned to the emergency support team under the epidemic prevention command. The Propaganda Department of the headquarters said that the emergency protection team would not be interviewed by reporters.

A staff member in charge of material collection at the hospital told China News weekly on February 11 that materials can only be supplied on a day-to-day basis at present, or that priority can only be given to first-line departments, and the supply hospitals themselves are hard to come by. "But this disease has an incubation period, and other general departments also need protection, " Ni said.

The cost of supplies is enormous. According to Ni Fang, the first three wards opened by the Department of respiratory medicine in the back Lake district, for example, have three shifts, with nurses and doctors checking rooms, and 100 sets of complete protective equipment, including protective clothing and masks, are consumed every day. According to a list of material requirements for the Central Hospital in Wuhan, obtained by China News Week, the hospital consumes 2,280 protective clothing per day, 4,560 N95 masks, 4,560 disposable isolation clothing and 2,280 protective face screens. But in an interview with China News weekly on Feb. 14, Ni said that for the past two days, because there was no isolation clothing, she had to wear a protective clothing of poor quality as isolation clothing, and then wear a protective clothing outside. Zhao Gang said, because the quality of protective clothing is not good, the surface has trachoma, can only be bound up with tape, and some protective clothing wear a squat down to hit a needle broken. And because the face screen, shoe cover is insufficient, the hospital medical staff also from time to time has takes the yellow plastic bag to cover on the head, the foot substitution phenomenon. Ni Fang said that in recent days, the hospital materials and raised a part of the shortage of temporary relief.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The number of emergency patients at central hospitals has also started to drop in the past week or two as the shelter and Vulcan Mountain hospitals have started taking in patients, Effen said. On Feb. 13, there were only 400 fever clinics in the Houhu district, and only a few dozen in the Nanjing Road district, and a large proportion of them were backlogged with noncritical patients for nucleic acid testing. But the beds are still very tight, even the state of overload operation.

On Feb. 12, Zhao said, a doctor at the hospital had to wait for a bed if he wanted to move in. The lack of medical equipment is also a difficult problem for the Central Hospital. Cai Yi, director of the Pain Department, said that his ward had four to five seriously ill patients who were unable to breathe freely and needed to be evacuated by a breathing machine, but only one or two such machines were available in his ward, there's not even one in the other wards.

But hospital admissions continue. After adjustment, Ni Fang's ward beds recently increased from 22 to 40, intensive care patients. A total of 300 additional beds will be added to the Central Hospital's Houhu and Nanjing Road Hospital areas. "there are still many patients who have not been admitted, " effin said.

To Ni's relief, the hospital assigned 10 more nurses to her on Feb. 14, meaning some of her colleagues could take a break.

(at the request of the interviewee, Li Yuan, Zhao Gang and Wang Yu were given pseudonyms.)
